abstract: |
  The H-1B visa program enables U.S. employers to hire foreign professionals in specialized occupations when qualified domestic workers are unavailable. This study examines how political and economic disruptions influenced H-1B petition outcomes between 2017 and 2023. Using data from the USCIS H-1B Employer Data Hub, we analyze trends in visa approvals, denials, and petition volumes during a period shaped by the COVID-19 pandemic and a transition between presidential administrations with differing immigration policies. After cleaning and merging multi-year datasets, we compute longitudinal denial rates, analyze petition volume patterns, and construct a normalized metric of recruitment vitality across major industry sectors. Our findings show that denial rates increased significantly during the Trump administration before declining sharply following policy reversals under the Biden administration. In addition, the COVID-19 pandemic temporarily reduced overall petition volume and shifted employer behavior toward retaining existing workers rather than recruiting new foreign talent. These results highlight the sensitivity of H-1B outcomes to both policy interpretation and macroeconomic conditions.
