## Background {#sec-intro}

The H-1B program is designed for employers seeking to hire nonimmigrant visitors as workers in specialty occupations. A specialty occupation can be defined as one that requires specialized knowledge and the attainment of at least a bachelor’s degree or its equivalent. The H-1B is intended to help employers who cannot obtain needed skills from the U.S. workforce by authorizing the temporary employment of qualified individuals who are not otherwise eligible to work in the United States.
In practice, however, H-1B sponsorship tends to be concentrated in certain industries. This concentration reflects the sectors where U.S. firms rely most heavily on highly trained foreign workers. The majority of authorized H-1B new hires nationally are employed in the Professional, Scientific, and Technical Services sector. Because these visas are closely tied to employment needs, broader economic conditions also influence visa demand and approval patterns. Despite the substantial slowdown in the growth of the U.S.-born labor force, immigration encourages economic expansion. This is because immigrants fill labor shortages while offsetting population aging since they tend to be younger and of working age.
While long-term economic dynamics shape immigration trends, short-term shocks can disrupt them significantly. One of the most dramatic disruptions in recent history was the COVID-19 pandemic; it resulted in a major disruption to the economy beginning in early 2020. When the pandemic struck, economic activity plummeted. However, by June 2022, total employment had surpassed its pre-pandemic level. Although the overall economy recovered, the pace of recovery varied across industries. Professional and business services as well as technology sectors recovered quickly because of their ability to shift to remote formats, while sectors dependent on in-person interaction experienced the slowest recoveries. Notably, the industries most affected by COVID-19 were travel, transportation, and tourism.
At the same time, immigration policy itself was undergoing major changes. From 2017 to 2023, immigration policy shifted dramatically between presidential administrations, moving from the Trump administration's “maximum pressure” approach between 2016–2020 to the Biden administration’s efforts to reverse many of these policies beginning in 2021. For the H-1B program specifically, the Trump administration increased scrutiny, which led to higher denial rates and a narrowing of key definitions. For example, the definition of “specialty occupation” was tightened to require that the bachelor’s degree be directly related to the position and that the position be so specialized that it could only be performed by an individual with a specific degree. Following this period of increased restrictions, the Biden administration attempted to reverse several of these policies. During Biden’s presidency, H-1B denial rates dropped to under 3%, and policy efforts shifted toward fair wages and worker protection. One change was the restoration of the “Prior Deference” policy, which instructed adjudicators to give weight to previous approvals when reviewing extension requests.
These policy shifts, combined with the economic disruption of COVID-19, had significant implications for international students. The “Trump effect” increased visa denials and introduced discussions about eliminating Optional Practical Training (OPT), which reduced international student confidence in studying in the United States. At the same time, the pandemic sharply reduced new international enrollment and caused processing delays that hindered graduates’ ability to secure work authorization. The reduced ability for international students to remain in the United States resulted in fewer skilled workers available to U.S. firms, particularly in STEM fields. Between 2017 and 2020, regulatory changes forced many graduates to return to their home countries despite strong demand for their skills. However, during the Biden administration, Students benefited from several policy adjustments. Extensions to the F-1 student visa allowed graduates to transition more easily from student status to an H-1B visa without employment gaps. Additionally, the definition of “specialty occupation” was clarified again so that while degree fields must relate to job duties, a broader range of qualifying fields could satisfy the requirement.
As a result, international graduates entering the labor market between 2020 and 2023 faced an especially uncertain environment. They encountered an unstable labor market shaped by both visa-related policy changes and pandemic-related disruptions. Even though Optional Practical Training (OPT) remained an expanding pathway to employment, many highly skilled workers were still forced to leave the country due to shifting visa regulations and processing delays, making it difficult for employers to hire talent in critical fields such as STEM.
Combining these shocks to the economy and changes to legislation has resulted in a highly uncertain environment for securing H-1B work authorization. Since the H-1B program sits at the intersection of labor market demand and immigration policy, changes to either can significantly affect the likelihood that foreign workers can work in the United States.

## Introduction {#sec-plots}

The H-1B is a non-immigrant visa allowing U.S. employers to temporarily hire foreign professionals in “specialty occupations” requiring theoretical or technical expertise. This visa is essential to the U.S. labor market as it allows companies to recruit for the positions when they cannot find qualified U.S. workers. The probability of securing work authorization is highly susceptible to change, often fluctuating in response to economic downturns and shifts in political policy. The H-1B visa program provides a clear example of this dynamic, as approval rates and employer demand are closely tied to both the health of the U.S. economy and the direction of federal immigration policy.
This project explores how two major disruptors, the COVID-19 pandemic and the transition between presidential administrations, altered the probability of securing work authorization in the years 2017-2023. Beyond macroeconomic analysis, this research offers practical value to the university community as it identifies which industries remained welcoming for international talent during crises, providing guidance for the 12% of UCLA students navigating an increasingly complex immigration landscape. 

## Literature Review {#sec-plots} 

During the Trump administration (2017–2021), several studies documented a sharp rise in H-1B denial rates driven by administrative policy changes rather than statutory reform. Research by the National Foundation for American Policy (2020) found that denial rates for initial H-1B employment petitions increased substantially between 2017 and 2019, particularly in specialty occupations, attributing this shift to heightened scrutiny and reinterpretation of eligibility standards. While this work establishes that approval probabilities became more restrictive under Trump, it largely focuses on aggregate trends rather than industry-specific disparities, leaving open the question of whether certain sectors, such as manufacturing, faced disproportionately higher denial rates during this period.

In 2020, during the period when COVID-19 was going rampant, and the Trump administration was taking office, it was reported that Trump signed a measure that would “prevent foreign workers from filling 525,000 jobs, according to White House estimates” (Miroff and Romm, 2020). This is reflected in one of our data visualizations, “Industry-Specific Denial Hurdles,” which reveals the drastic rise of denial rates in the six industries shown in the visual. Additionally, it wasn’t just preventing H1-B or foreign applicants from being able to obtain jobs in the U.S.; Trump also ordered a hiring freeze or “a pause” that affected “more than half of the approximately 460,000 immigration visas issued last year”  (Miroff and Romm, 2020). Due to these new restrictions, companies would be scrambling to find solutions for their hiring process involving H1-B applicants, and some companies had to choose to deny these applications to avoid attention from the government and/or delay the hiring process.

	After the pandemic and Biden started to run the government administration, it was reported that the “United States appears to have bounced back from steep declines sparked by COVID-19… and restrictive policies of the Trump administration” (Chishti and Gelatt, 2022). This was possible due to the issuing of “more visas in FY 2022 than in FY 2019,” and the effects that came from the restriction were that the U.S. faced the “exacerbated labor shortage in certain industries and areas of the country” (Chishti and Gelatt, 2022). Our same data visualization reflects the drastic drop in the denial rate. For the heatmap “Geographic Disparities in Approval,” we can see that the Republican states, such as Texas and Georgia, wouldn’t switch easily during the Biden administration; thus, we’re still seeing these states with a high denial rate and still in the process of recovering.

## Statistical Methodology {#sec-plots} 

To evaluate H-1B visa trends amidst shifting political landscapes, we aggregated USCIS H-1B Employer Data Hub records from fiscal years 2017 to 2023. Our methodology began with cleaning and merging these multi-year datasets to standardize inconsistent column definitions, followed by mapping North American Industry Classification System (NAICS) codes into distinct industry sectors to reduce noise. We then employed longitudinal data aggregation and ratio normalization to assess shifts in petition outcomes across three primary dimensions. First, we calculated longitudinal denial rates, defined as initial denials divided by the sum of initial approvals and initial denials, to identify outcome volatility across different presidential administrations. Second, to analyze the petition volume and policy landscape, raw counts were categorized by case status, summed annually into a stacked temporal series, and overlaid with categorical shading to correlate volume fluctuations with specific administrative eras. Finally, to measure new talent acquisition velocity, we derived a relational metric by dividing initial petitions by the total adjudicated volume across the six most active NAICS sectors. This normalization allowed for a comparative assessment of "recruitment vitality" across industries of disparate scales, independent of their absolute petition volumes.

##Discussion {#sec-plots} 
The results of this analysis illustrate how the probability of securing H-1B work authorization is shaped by forces beyond labor market demand alone. The longitudinal denial rate analysis reveals that policy interpretation under different presidential administrations had a measurable impact on visa outcomes. Denial rates increased sharply between 2017 and 2020, aligning with the Trump administration’s intensified scrutiny of H-1B petitions and reinterpretation of the “specialty occupation” requirement. This suggests that regulatory enforcement, even without statutory reform, can significantly alter the accessibility of work authorization for foreign professionals.
At the same time, the petition volume analysis demonstrates how economic disruptions interact with policy changes. The COVID-19 pandemic produced a visible contraction in total petition volume as hiring slowed across industries. However, the magnitude of this contraction varied across sectors. Industries capable of remote work, particularly professional and technical services, recovered more rapidly than sectors dependent on physical presence. This divergence reinforces the importance of industry structure in shaping opportunities for foreign workers during economic shocks.
The normalized “recruitment vitality” metric further highlights how industries differed in their willingness to bring in new international talent during periods of uncertainty. Even when total petition volume declined, some sectors maintained relatively stable proportions of initial petitions, indicating continued reliance on foreign talent pipelines. Other industries shifted toward extensions and retention of existing workers rather than recruiting new applicants. This shift suggests that during periods of regulatory or economic uncertainty, employers may prioritize maintaining their existing workforce over navigating the risks associated with new visa sponsorship.
Finally, the geographic and industry-level patterns identified in the visualizations suggest that the impact of immigration policy changes was not uniform across the country. Certain states and sectors continued to experience elevated denial rates even after federal policy changes began to reverse earlier restrictions. These disparities may reflect differences in adjudication practices, employer familiarity with the visa process, or regional industry composition.
Taken together, these findings indicate that H-1B outcomes are shaped by the interaction of three major forces: immigration policy interpretation, macroeconomic conditions, and industry-level labor demand. The volatility observed between 2017 and 2023 highlights the sensitivity of the visa system to administrative priorities, reinforcing the idea that international professionals face a labor market where opportunities are influenced as much by policy context as by economic need.
 
##Conclusion {#sec-plots} 

This study examined how shifting presidential administrations and the COVID-19 pandemic reshaped H-1B visa outcomes across industries from 2017 to 2023. Together, the denial rate analysis and petition volume analysis paint a cohesive picture of a system highly sensitive to both political will and economic conditions. The findings confirm that H-1B visa outcomes were shaped less by shifts in labor demands than by the political environment. Denial rates climbed steeply during the Trump administration, peaking most severely before collapsing under Biden’s policy reversals. This volatility, driven by reinterpretation rather than statutory change, underscores how precarious work authorization can be for foreign-born professionals when eligibility standards shift with little warning.
Layered on top of this political dynamic, the COVID-19 pandemic triggered a broad pivot away from new recruitment toward retaining existing workers. The recovery that followed was uneven across sectors, as industries capable of remote work regained momentum more quickly than others. Geographic disparities linked to political background further complicated the recovery, as certain states remained slow to reflect national-level policy improvements.
The practical takeaway is that approval prospects depend heavily on industry choices and timing relative to political cycles, not qualification alone. As immigration policy enters another period of potential restriction, the patterns identified here offer a basis for anticipating where new barriers are likely to emerge, and which sectors have historically offered more stable pathways into the U.S. workforce.

